You hit the nail on the head. A 100% rigid block would turn the story into a breathless, mechanical checklist and completely suffocate the narrative. We need space for the audience to breathe, for atmospheric worldbuilding, for humor, and for quiet reflection.

What we really need to police is **"false activity"**—the illusion of agency where a character is talking a lot or feeling a lot, but not actually *doing* anything that impacts the plot.

Interestingly, your research provides a fantastic nuance here: AI actually *over-indexes* on protagonist-driven resolutions compared to human authors (69% vs. 46%). AI models desperately want the main character to neatly solve everything, whereas human writers are much more comfortable with ambiguous endings or external fates.

Here is the blueprint for a balanced, nuanced Agency Enforcement Protocol.

